Async JavaScript functions can be tricky to work with, and there are several common mistakes to watch out for. Here are some of the most common ones:

1. **Not awaiting promises**: When calling an async function, you need to use the `await` keyword to pause the execution of the code until the promise is resolved or rejected. If you don't use `await`, the function will return a promise instead of the result.

   ```javascript
// Bad practice
async function myFunction() {
  const result = await fetch('https://example.com/api/data');
  console.log(result); // This will log the promise, not the result
}

// Good practice
async function myFunction() {
  const result = await fetch('https://example.com/api/data');
  console.log(await result.json()); // This will log the result
}
```

2. **Not handling errors**: Async functions can throw errors, and if you don't handle them, the error will propagate up the call

A `NullPointerException` in Java typically occurs when you try to use an object that has not been initialized or is null. Here are some general steps to help you fix a `NullPointerException`:

1. **Identify the line of code that's causing the error**: Look at the stacktrace or error message to determine which line of code is causing the `NullPointerException`.

2. **Check for null values**: Make sure that the object you're trying to use is not null. You can do this by adding a null check before using the object.

   ```java
if (obj!= null) {
    // Use the object
} else {
    // Handle the case where the object is null
}
```

3. **Initialize the object**: If the object is null, make sure it's properly initialized before using it.

   ```java
MyObject obj = new MyObject();
```

